<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-09-30T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-09-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="1164" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1164">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.6363/139.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                Vice Consul <persName type="to">Bevan</persName>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-09-30">
                                    <hi rend="italic">September 30, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department has received your despatch
                            No. 1210 of September 12, 1914, relative to the interpretation of the
                            decree affecting oil lands recently issued by Governor Candido Aguilar
                            of the State of Vera Cruz, Mexico, and saying that you have addressed a
                            letter upon the subject to the Governor.</p>
                        <p>The Department awaits the receipt of the Governor’s reply to the inquiry
                            addressed to him.</p>
                        <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>For the Secretary of State: <lb/>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilbur J. Carr</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>